European Defence and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is down to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that the occupation by the Nazis.
It may be due to living in a country in the middle of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of Europe's spiritual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations for centuries.
Maybe all these factors combined have led me to the conclusion that Europe is a single political entity whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever – one democratic, stable, prosperous and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous and isolated – is a misconception.
That's like one part of the room being heated while the other part stays cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event sends an echo throughout Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to take in the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest –, a number of essential tasks have to be tackled, both within the new democracies and within the European as well as the Atlantic community.
Initially, Europe must promote community in post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe therefore must help its new democracies to become an organic part of a shared continental commitment to deepening and strengthening civil society.
The more diverse and interconnected European civil society structures become, the better equipped new democracies will be for membership in the EU and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer various solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution is, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their organizations.
A genuine solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest basis for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation of Munich.
This experience is still a powerful call to vigilance.
Evil must be confronted as soon as it appears, but simply having governments act is not enough.
Governance policy emerges from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Worry about safety is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept of its security policy.
It should stand out through an ability to quickly make decisions and quickly implement joint decisions - reforms that recent developments in Yugoslavia have proven to be necessary.
The NATO intervention in the past year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of overall European security require interventions outside EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better it is.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate does not come into play, although an intervention would be in the interest of many people, all of Europe, indeed even human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared for it, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
However, further measures are still needed in the field of preventive security, but even more is necessary in order for this security to reflect the values of the expanded European civil society.
Tens of thousands of human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had taken action at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horrors, people acted only timidly.
These shortcomings were the result of various individual domestic policy interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo happen.
Europe cannot remain dependent on the US forever, especially not when it comes to European problems.
It must be able to reach its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can continue to exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves to be incapable of agreeing on means and ways to protect human rights not only on its territory but also in areas that may join it one day.
Such an EU expansion is only then conceivable if it progresses hand in hand with a courageous reform of the EU institutions.
I am confident that the government conference will submit practical proposals for institutional reform to further the Union.
But I consider this as the start of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting endeavor to accelerate and make the EU decision-making process more transparent.
A related point to institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not be simply outvoted by the larger ones, while still taking account of the size of the individual states.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; its members are not directly elected, but elected by the parliaments of the member states from their own ranks.
The first EU chamber – i.e. the current parliament – would thus reflect the size of individual member states, the second chamber would, with the same number of representatives for each state, increase equality.
Sooner or later, these changes will require that the EU has a clear, comprehensible constitution - a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and obligations of both European citizens and states, the underlying values, and the significance and objectives of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their principal powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a basic law would not mean an automatic transformation of the current union into a federal superstate that is feared by Euro-skeptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, understand it better, see the importance of the EU for their lives, and, consequently, identify with it.
